 name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda Folkroy was born in 1328, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, Adam Folkroy, was 46 and her mother, Mrs. Adam Folkroy, was 42. She married Sir John Swete Wemund  Austyn about 1346, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1328–":"1328–Surnud","1312–1363":"1312–1363","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","1304–Male":"1304–Surnud","1347–1431":"1347–1431","1282–Male":"1282–Surnud","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","1304":"1304","1347":"1347","1312":"1312","about 1347":"umbes 1347","1431":"1431","1286":"1286","1363":"1363","about 1346":"umbes 1346","1282":"1282","1328":"1328","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, Englan